---
import Book from "../layouts/Book.astro";
import ChapterOpener from "../components/ChapterOpener.astro";
import Production from "../components/grammar/Production.astro";
import OperatorEntry from "../components/grammar/OperatorEntry.astro";
---

<Book title="Grammar" chapter="grammar" description="The full grammar of Luna Pipes, five operators, four primitives, one production tree.">
  <ChapterOpener
    num="02"
    word="Grammar"
    subtitle="Five operators, four primitives, one production tree. The whole language fits on a postcard."
    example={'<pipe> ::= <stage> ( ">>" <stage> )*'}
  />

  <section class="wrap intro">
    <p>
      Luna Pipes is a concatenative expression language. A program is a
      sequence of <em>stages</em> separated by operators. There are no
      statements, no blocks, no return values to track. The value flows
      left-to-right; each operator decides how the next stage receives it.
    </p>
    <p>
      The grammar below is given in EBNF. The semantics follow in plain
      English, with one runnable example per operator. Whitespace is
      insignificant; identifiers are case-sensitive; the operator
      <code>&gt;&gt;</code> is right-associative.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap ebnf">
    <h2>Production rules.</h2>
    <div class="prod-list">
      <Production name="pipe" rule={'<stage> ( ">>" <stage> )*'} note="A pipe is one or more stages chained with the pipe operator." />
      <Production name="stage" rule={'<verb> <arg>* <modifier>?'} note="A stage is a verb followed by zero or more arguments and an optional modifier." />
      <Production name="verb" rule={'"/" <identifier>'} note="A verb is a leading slash followed by an identifier. Identifiers may contain a-z, 0-9, hyphen." />
      <Production name="arg" rule={'<string> | <number> | <flag>'} note="An argument is a quoted string, a number, or a flag of the form --name or --name=value." />
      <Production name="flag" rule={'"--" <identifier> ( "=" <value> )?'} />
      <Production name="modifier" rule={'<repeat> | <parallel> | <conditional> | <sink>'} note="A stage can carry one modifier. Modifiers attach to the stage they follow." />
      <Production name="repeat" rule={'"*" <integer>'} note="Repeat the preceding stage N times, in parallel." />
      <Production name="parallel" rule={'"||" <stage>'} note="Fan out: run the previous stage and this stage concurrently; join the results." />
      <Production name="conditional" rule={'"?" <flag> ">>" <pipe> ":" <pipe>'} note="Branch on a truthy flag." />
      <Production name="sink" rule={'"!"'} note="Run the preceding stage for effect; discard its output." />
    </div>
    <p>
      That is the full grammar. The runtime is responsible for resolving
      verbs to skills, for marshaling arguments, and for serializing the
      output of one stage as the input of the next. See
      <a href="https://github.com/lunaos/luna-agents">the source</a> for the parser.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="wrap ops">
    <h2>Operators.</h2>

    <OperatorEntry
      glyph=">>"
      name="pipe"
      arity="binary, left input feeds right input"
      semantics="The pipe operator passes the output of the left stage as the input of the right stage. It is the only required operator: a Luna Pipes program with no operators is one stage, executed alone."
      example={'/persona generate >> ghost "launch post"'}
      output={['composed: 2 stages, sequential', '  /persona generate → 4 personas', '  ghost "launch post" → 4 drafts']}
    />

    <OperatorEntry
      glyph="*"
      name="repeat"
      arity="unary postfix, takes an integer"
      semantics="Repeat the preceding stage N times in parallel. The repeated stage receives the same input N times; outputs are joined into an array for the next stage."
      example={'/persona generate >> ghost "post" *4 >> publish notion'}
      output={['composed: 6 stages, ghost runs 4 times concurrently', 'join: 4 drafts → publish (1 stage)']}
    />

    <OperatorEntry
      glyph="||"
      name="fanout"
      arity="binary, both stages run concurrently"
      semantics="Run the left and right stages in parallel against the same input. Their outputs are joined as a tuple and passed to the next stage. Use for embarrassingly parallel work where the two branches do different things."
      example={'/persona generate >> ghost "post" || imagine "hero" >> publish notion'}
      output={['composed: 4 stages, fanout join', '  ghost   → text', '  imagine → image', 'join → publish']}
    />

    <OperatorEntry
      glyph="?"
      name="conditional"
      arity="ternary, branches on a truthy flag"
      semantics="Branch on the named flag from the input. The left sub-pipe runs if the flag is truthy; the right runs otherwise. Either side is a full pipe expression."
      example={'/persona generate >> ? premium >> ghost "longform" : ghost "short"'}
      output={['composed: branches on premium', '  premium=true  → longform path', '  premium=false → short path']}
    />

    <OperatorEntry
      glyph="!"
      name="sink"
      arity="unary postfix, no input to the next stage"
      semantics="Run the preceding stage for effect. The runtime executes it, awaits completion, then discards its output. Useful for notifications, logs, or side-effects that should not contaminate the value flowing through."
      example={'/persona generate >> ghost "post" >> publish notion >> notify slack !'}
      output={['composed: 4 stages, notify runs, output discarded']}
    />
  </section>

  <section class="wrap closing">
    <h2>Errata.</h2>
    <p>
      The grammar is closed for v1. The lexicon is open. New verbs ship in
      every release; new operators do not. If you find yourself wanting one,
      compose two existing ones first; if the composition is awkward, file
      an issue with the example.
    </p>
  </section>
</Book>

<style>
  .intro { padding: var(--t-6) 0 var(--t-4); }
  .ebnf { padding: var(--t-6) 0 var(--t-8); }
  .prod-list {
    margin: var(--t-3) 0;
    border-top: 1px solid var(--rule);
    max-width: var(--measure-wide);
  }
  .ops { padding-top: var(--t-4); }
  .closing { padding: var(--t-6) 0 var(--t-12); }
  .closing p { max-width: var(--measure); }
</style>
